30.       Coordination with other GEF and non- GEF funded projects: As indicated in the baseline scenario, many initiatives are being carried out in the project intervention area in order to support food security and water resources management actions. However, knowledge of the dynamics of these critical ecosystems and stakeholder coordination as well as the development of a sustainable approach to integrated ecosystem management of oases and valleys are still a great challenge. Furthermore, in the project intervention area, there are places where the issue of biodiversity conservation is very critical, particularly the protected areas and important species of the fauna and flora. By targeting the above-mentioned conservation objectives in the oasis ecosystems and focusing on water management for agricultural production to improve biodiversity, the project will support the objectives of GEF-6 BD. 4 program 9 which are mainly to target specific and thematic interventions. The oasis ecosystem target will provide the opportunity to creating many ecosystem services in this difficult environment. The ecosystem services will include biodiversity restoration and conservation; improve water resources management, sustainable agricultural practices and integrity of the Protected Areas (PA) systems.      Link with GEF financed projects      31.       UNDP/GEF Project for co-management of Air and Ténéré Resources (COGERAT): the overall objective of the project is to contribute to land degradation control and conservation of the Saharan ecosystems in Northern Niger through integration of the local development and decentralization processes. Specifically, COGERAT should put in place a decentralized system of land and natural resources management of the RNNAT and its related areas in order to reverse the trends of environmental degradation and improve the living conditions of resident populations. The IOEMP- NN (PGIEO-NN) will contribute to the implementation of the State-Communes agreement for co-management of the resources of Aïr and Ténéré National Nature Reserve and the Sustainable Ecotourism Charter drawn up within COGERAT framework. The co-management agreement will be updated and expanded to take into account the issue of oasis observatories and the national oasis management strategy.     33.    UNDP/GEF - Niger Fauna Corridors Project (NFCP).  The aims of the project is to strengthen the policy, legal and institutional framework in order to improve the management of Protected Areas (PA) through new public-private partnerships that will reduce the costs and create favorable conditions for their conservation. It will support the creation of an interconnected PA complex in northern Niger, based on the protected areas of Aïr-Ténéré, Termit Tin Toumma and Gadabedji. The protected areas are interconnected by wildlife corridors strategically defined as part of a participatory and sustainable management of land use. Biodiversity value chains, with especially community sport hunting concessions, will generate revenue for communities, local authorities and PAs, thus promoting conservation. The goal of the project is to protect this biodiversity of global importance in the Niger Saharan biome through a system of interconnected protected areas.     33.    IFAD/GEF Family Farming Development Program (ProDAF): the aim of this project is to contribute to sustainable food and nutrition security and rural households’ resilience to crises in the four regions of Maradi, Tahoua and Zinder. ProDAF is structured around three (3) components, namely: (i) Sustainable development of family farming, (ii) Access to markets, Monitoring-Evaluation and Knowledge Management. Under Component 1 on Sustainable Family Farming, the following activities have been planned: (i) productive structuring to increase water rational management and soil fertility, and thus the resilience of family farms, (ii) Strengthening production, post-production and organization capacities of rural actors. The theme addressed under component 1 of ProDAF is directly linked to conservation measures that will be implemented in this oasis project. The development cluster approach used in PRODAF is linked to the integrated landscape planning.     34.    UNDP/GEF Oasis Basins Silting Control Project (PLECO). The aim of this project in the departments of Gouré and Maïné-soroa is to ensure a sustainable management of lands and water resources in order to improve the livelihood and incomes of the populations. More specifically, PLECO aims at protecting the integrity of the basins ecosystems in Gouré and Maïné-soroa departments and improving their agro-sylvo-pastoral productivity. The Project is structured around three (3) components: (i) Improvement of local practices relating to land management and oasis ecosystems, (ii) Capacity building of institutions and local communities for SLM, (iii) establishment of a system for monitoring of oasis land siltation and degradation. As the link between the two projects is well established, the IOEMP-NN will build on the achievements and lessons learned from PLECO in the management of oasis ecosystems. The National Ecosystem Management Strategy that will be approved under the IOEMP -NN will deal with oasis issues in the PLECO intervention area.     35.    WB/GEF- Community Action Program Phase 3 (PAC 3): in addition to the achievements of the previous phases, the project envisages to restore, at least 100 ha of degraded land in each of the 125 communes of its intervention area. This will lead to the implementation of SLWM practices to enable an appropriate management of natural resources initiated by the populations through application of techniques designed to ensure sustainable agricultural production based g on the natural and social specificities of the region. So, by its component A, the PAC3 contributes to the promotion of SLWM through capacity building for actors to enable them conducting agro-silvo-pastoral and fisheries activities and improving the sustainable land and water management. These actions, carried out in component B of the project, will allow increasing the productivity of agriculture and livestock activities leading to food security of the populations, improving the conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity and maintaining the equipment’s and services of the ecosystems, through a range of sustainable practices and techniques including erosion control and reforestation. The approach adopted for the implementation of PAC 3 activities focuses on the communal project management that will also be developed as part of the integrated landscape planning of the IOEMP -NN.     Link with other initiatives      36.       The IOEMP will contribute to the achievements of the commitments of Niger Republic under the African Forest and Landscape Restoration Initiative (AFR100) and Bonn challenge by which the country undertook to restore 3.2 million hectares by year 2030. The project will also contribute to the implementation of the Great Green Wall Initiative and African Initiative for Desertification Control. At the local level, the IOEMP constitutes one of the operational elements of 3N Initiative "Nigeriens feed Nigeriens".Benefits37.       The Region of Agadez contains various ecosystems, especially in the oases, plains, valleys and mountains which provide important goods and services for the socio-economic well-being of local communities, but are also of global importance. The project is conceived with the twin-goals of (i) promoting sustainable management of oases and valleys, thereby contributing to the generation of environmental benefits of global importance; and (ii) improving the socio-economic well-being of communities who heavily depend on the oases and valley ecosystems through the proposed suite of interventions to be executed by the State, the Municipalities, the Technical and Financial Partners and other Mining companies. The aim of the project is to promote environmental advantages in the form of integrated oasis ecosystems management through reforestation and concerted natural resources management thus contributing in social benefits in the form of improved incomes, safe livelihoods and a better distribution of economic benefits. The project will seek to build capacities among local users of oases and forest ecosystem services in view to improving their ability to sustainably manage the resources for their socio-economic well-being. The project will carry out awareness and mobilization campaigns for the various stakeholders in order to engage them in the process of inter-municipal planning. To support the generation of socio-economic benefits, a diagnosis of the ecological and socioeconomic (agriculture, pastoral, etc.) dynamics of the oasis and arid valley forests ecosystems of the Aïr Massif will be undertaken. A common set of environmental and socioeconomic indicators for monitoring oasis and arid valley forests ecosystems of Aïr Massif will be integrated in all the ILMPs. These improvements in food production and socio-economic development of the local communities will reduce biodiversity loss and land degradation.

22.     The project will provide monetary and non-monetary benefits to the local stakeholders, including community members, small-scale farmers, herders and forestry workers, users of non-timber forest products and individuals and small businesses owners involved / interested in tourism. These benefits will include: a) implementation of sustainable agro-silvo-pastoral practices including CSA and SLM practices, implementation of improved rangeland, pasture and forest management in the selected pilot sites, implementation of improved resource management in village hunting areas, including a revision of the governance of community-managed areas to ensure a fair and equitable sharing of the benefits related to resource use, and an increase in the income level of participating households; b) technical and financial support and training to members of local communities to implement improved land and resource management practices; c) support for the establishment of small enterprises involved in sustainable forest products processing, including support for their organization into cooperatives, provision of technical training and equipment, securing access to the resources that support the value chains and the sustainability of their use, including through the certification of forest areas where women collect the shea fruits that are processed as part of the shea butter value chain, and providing support for the marketing of the products, and an increase in the income level of participating women and men; d) technical and financial support to establish sustainable community tourism enterprises related to protected areas or to improve existing ones, including trainings for local community members interested in getting involved in tourism activities or existing small enterprises related to tourism, support for the development or improvement of tourism products and to facilitate access to markets, and an increase in the income level of participating women and men; e) capacity building for community / village structures concerned with the collaborative management of PAs to enable them to fulfil the role expected of them in the collaborative PA management process. These benefits will translate in supporting the achievement of global environmental benefits through increasing forest, pasture and farming areas under improved and sustainable practices.  23.     At the national level, the project is contributing to institutional capacity building that will benefit Government staff from the Ministry of Environment, Green Economy and Climate Change and its regional decentralized directions, including the staff from the Permanent Secretariat of the National Council for Sustainable Development (SP/CNDD), the Directorate General of Waters and Forests (DGWF), the National Office of Protected Areas (OFINAP), the Regional Directorates of Environment, Green Economy and Climate Change and their subdivisions, and local authorities (collectivités locales). The capacity development of these stakeholders will focus on the environmental land-use planning process at the landscape scale and on various aspects of protected area management, including collaborative management involving local communities adjacent to protected areas, so that the main groups of stakeholders are able to fulfil the role expected of them in the collaborative PA management process. These benefits will translate in supporting the achievement of global environmental benefits through increasing the management effectiveness of the protected areas and the conservation of biodiversity.  24.     Through the conservation and sustainable use of land and natural resources and habitats (e.g., non-timber forest products, forests, pastures and rangelands, agroecosystems,), ecosystem services will be enhanced (soil, habitat for biodiversity, carbon stocks, nutrient cycling, climate regulation, and natural assets for tourism) with a positive impact on the well-being of the local communities across the PONASI landscape. The project is expected to directly benefit 18,531 women and 12,354 men.

1.         National project beneficiaries can be segregated into several groups/levels as follows:   -      Government staff (senior including politicians and parliamentarians, but especially technicians) in both the national central government and the regional government in Príncipe, which will benefit from technical training and on-the-job exposure to new approaches, methodologies and technologies/equipment regarding the legal and institutional framework, environmental law enforcement, land use planning and biodiversity mainstreaming, biodiversity and ecosystem service science, biodiversity and threat monitoring (MOBMS), PA management, PA/biodiversity financing, improved charcoal kilns, sustainable charcoal sourcing based on coconut, as well as an access to experience from past project and experience in other countries. The economic benefits can accrue by salary increases and/or better employability post-project including in consultancy roles. The benefits to these technicians translate into benefits to all the GEB by the project, during the project itself and especially also post-project. Gender issues will be respected by ensuring that training and employment involves women in an equitable if not preferential manner.  -      NGO staff and young academics, because the project aims to help build a new cohort of national biodiversity conservation specialists, through subsidised post-graduate courses, subsidised internships in the project and NGOs abroad, trainings in STP. The GEB targeted here are not bound to materialise during the project but through a project legacy that will have a favourable impact on the management of STP’s globally relevant biodiversity in the long-term. Gender issues will be respected by ensuring that training opportunities are provided to women in an equitable if not preferential manner.  -      At the local community level, where stakeholders will benefit from support provided by one gender-focused community organiser per island in addition to technical assistance by the wider team made up of the DGA-hosted PMU, the government agencies involved (DFB, RSESD) and the Responsible Party BirdLife International. This this support will involve i) strengthening of communities and CBOs; ii) demonstration and acquisition of improved model charcoal kilns; iv) employment as eco-guides and in supplementary planting of fast-growing charcoal trees; iii) capacity development on issues relating to environmental law enforcement including community-based surveillance, PA governance and biodiversity, sustainable charcoal and sustainable livelihood diversification; and iv) the issuance of micro-grants by the project for sustainable livelihood diversification (sustainable charcoal initiatives such as improved kilns, briquettes, biogas, sustainable exploitation of NTFP, ecotourism, apiculture, sustainable forestry, agroforestry, etc.). Special attention will also be given to community-level gender issues and women empowerment. These beneficiaries will be targeted in such a manner that the benefits will lead to a reduction of unsustainable natural resource exploitation most especially selective logging for charcoal-making and thereby improve the outlook for natural forests of STP and the globally important biodiversity they contain, inside and outside the 2 islands’ two NPs.
